Everyone’s Googling React 20 — but the real story is even more useful.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Everyone is looking for this if you are searching “React 20”, and about to save yourself from a lot of confusion.
There is no React 20 yet. React 19.2 is what makes it out the door, and that’s a level of structural change that could easily lead to major version-bump assumptions on someone’s part.
What actually landed in 19.2
useEffectEvent — a new, clean way of reading the latest props/state inside an Effect without pulling them into the dependency array (re: #22646). No more gymnastics with useRef to retrieve stale closures.
// before: ref juggling to avoid stale closures
const onScrollEvent = useEffectEvent((currentTheme) => {
logScrollPosition(currentTheme);
});useEffect(() => {
const handler = () => onScrollEvent(theme);
window.addEventListener('scroll', handler);
return () => window.removeEventListener('scroll', handler);
}, []); // theme intentionally left out — useEffectEvent handles it
Activity — allows you to keep the state of a component alive while masking it from the DOM. Done for tabs or offscreen routes, or to keep scroll position in a list you have gone away from
